The '''Eastern Caribbean Gas Pipeline''' is a proposed natural gas pipeline from [[Tobago]] to other eastern Caribbean islands.
== History== The idea had its genesis with [[Patrick Manning]], Prime Minister of [[Trinidad and Tobago]], who announced in 2002 that his country was going to undertake one of the largest civil engineering projects in the Caribbean region.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}
The project suffered a brief setback when [[Venezuela]]n leader [[Hugo Chavez]] petitioned intensely that the pipeline should instead originate from [[Venezuela]] and reach further into the north, including [[Cuba]] and the [[United States]].<ref name=ogj290903>{{cite news |url=http://www.ogj.com/articles/2003/09/trinidad-and-tobago-venezuela-mull-over-caribbean-us-natural-gas-pipeline.html |title=Trinidad and Tobago, Venezuela mull over Caribbean-US natural gas pipeline |first=Curtis |last=Williams |date=29 September 2003 |work=[[Oil & Gas Journal]] |publisher=[[PennWell Corporation]] |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20031002153956/http://ogj.pennnet.com/articles/web_article_display.cfm?Section=OnlineArticles&ARTICLE_CATEGORY=Trasp&ARTICLE_ID=188398 |archivedate=2 October 2003 |deadurl=no |accessdate=5 March 2010 |df= }}</ref>
In March 2010 the [[Barbados]] indicated after a two-year hiatus that it would seek to move toward the negotiations stage for the first stage of the pipeline from Tobago to Barbados.<ref>{{cite news |title=177 miles of gas pipe from Tobago to Barbados |url=http://www.cbc.bb/content/view/10813/10/ |agency=[[Caribbean Broadcasting Corporation]] |date=15 May 2007 |accessdate=5 March 2010 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070826214214/http://www.cbc.bb/content/view/10813/10/ |archivedate=26 August 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Barbados government to negotiate importation of natural gas from Trinidad |first=Julie |last=Wilson |url=http://www.caribbeannetnews.com/news-21820--26-26--.html |publisher=CaribbeanNetNews.com |date=3 March 2010 |accessdate=5 March 2010 }}{{dead link|date=January 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Importing natural gas won’t have immediate effect on fuel prices |author= |first=N. |last=B. |url=http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&NewsID=9277 |newspaper=[[Barbados Advocate]] |date=4 March 2010 |accessdate=5 March 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120326081725/http://www.barbadosadvocate.com/newsitem.asp?more=business&NewsID=9277 |archivedate=26 March 2012 |df= }}</ref>
==Network== The overall pipeline would be {{convert|596|mi}} long, including shore approaches and the lateral line to Barbados.<ref name=ogj290903/> The first {{convert|177|mi|adj=on}} long stage would start from the Cove Point Estate in Tobago and run to Barbados.<ref name=caribbean120112>{{cite news |url= http://www.caribbean360.com/business/547868.html |title=Eastern Caribbean gas pipeline coming back on stream |date=12 January 2012 |work=Caribbean360 |accessdate= 23 December 2012 }}</ref><ref name=gleaner140312>{{cite news |url= http://jamaica-gleaner.com/gleaner/20120314/business/business7.html |title= Gas pipeline project makes headway |date=14 March 2012 |newspaper = [[Gleaner Company|The Gleaner]] |accessdate= 23 December 2012 }}</ref> The second stage it would be expanded to [[Saint Lucia]], [[Dominica]], [[Martinique]], and [[Guadeloupe]].
== Project company == The project is developed by the Eastern Caribbean Gas Pipeline Company Limited (ECGPC). 60% of the company is jointly owned by the United States companies Beowulf Energy LLC and First Reserve Energy International Fund. Rest is owned by the Trinidad and Tobago companies Guardian Holdings (15%), [[Unit Trust Corporation]] (15%), and the [[National Gas Company of Trinidad and Tobago]] (10%).<ref name=gleaner140312/>
